div.p:
In the consulship of Tiberius Caesar (for the third time), and Germanicus Caesar (for the second), when Gnaeus Acceius Rufus Lutatius of the Arnensus tribe, son of Gnaeus, and Titus Petillius, son of Publius, of the Quirina tribe, were duovirs, it was decreed that: a shrine, these statues, and a sacrifical animal for the dedication [were voted]. 
                    For the birthday of Augustus, 8 days before the Kalends of October, two victims, which are customarily to be sacrificed in perpetuity at the altar which has been dedicated to the Augustan Numen, ought to be sacrificed on the 9th and 8th days before the Kalends of October. 
                    Likewise, on the birthday of Tiberius Caesar, the decurions and people should dine in perpetuity, which expense Quintus Cascellius Labeo promises in perpetuity, in order that he be given thanks for his munificence; and on this same birthday, so that a calf may be sacrificed annually.
                    And on the birthdays of Augustus and Tiberius, the Caesars, before the decurions proceed to dine, their Genii should be invited to dine at the altar of the Augustan Numen with wine and incense. We have had built at our own expense an altar to the Augustan Numen; we have had supervised games for six days from the Ides of August at our own expense;
                    on the birthday of the Augusta we gave wine and cakes to the women from the places of the town for the Bona Dea at our own expense. Likewise, at the dedication of statues to the Caesars and the Augusta, we gave wine and cakes at our own expense to the decurions and the people, and we vowed to give them in perpetuity on the anniversary of the dedication;
                    so that day may be better attended every year, we will observe this six days before the Ides of March, the day on which Tiberius Caesar was very happily made the chief priest.
